🧠 B. Fortune Telling — FULL NOTES
⚙️ Problem in one line

You start from a number d and for each ai you can:

d = d + ai
d = d ^ ai

👉 You need to check: who (Alice or Bob) can reach y

🔥 CORE IDEA (MOST IMPORTANT)

👉 We DON’T care about exact value

👉 We only care about parity (even / odd)

🧪 PARITY RULES (VERY IMPORTANT)
➕ Addition Rules
even + even = even
odd + odd = even
even + odd = odd
odd + even = odd
⊕ XOR Rules

Think in last bit:

even ^ even = even
odd ^ odd = even
even ^ odd = odd
odd ^ even = odd
⚡ BIG OBSERVATION

👉 Addition and XOR behave EXACTLY SAME for parity

Operation	Result
even + even	even
even ^ even	even
odd + odd	even
odd ^ odd	even
even + odd	odd
even ^ odd	odd
🧠 FINAL CONCLUSION

👉 Each ai affects parity like this:

if ai is even → no change
if ai is odd → flips parity
🔄 TOTAL EFFECT

Let:

odd_count = number of odd elements in array

Then:

if odd_count is even → parity same
if odd_count is odd → parity flips
⚡ SHORTCUT (VERY IMPORTANT)

👉 Instead of counting odd:

sum % 2 == odd_count % 2

So just use:

sum = a1 + a2 + ... + an
👤 ALICE vs BOB
Alice:
start = x
final parity = (x + sum) % 2
Bob:
start = x + 3

But:

3 is odd → flips parity

So:

(x + 3) % 2 = x % 2 ^ 1

👉 Bob’s parity is opposite of Alice

🎯 FINAL LOGIC

👉 Only ONE of them can match y

So:

If (x + sum) % 2 == y % 2
→ Alice
Else
→ Bob
💡 INTUITION (IMPORTANT FOR MEMORY)

👉 Alice can only produce numbers with parity:

(x + sum) % 2

👉 Bob can only produce numbers with opposite parity:

(x + sum + 1) % 2
🔥 So:
If y matches Alice → she did it
Otherwise → Bob did it
🚀 WHY NO NEED TO CHECK OPERATIONS?

Because:

👉 No matter what sequence of + and ^ you choose
👉 parity outcome will always be SAME

So:

Order doesn’t matter
Choice doesn’t matter
Only parity matters
🧪 MINI DRY RUN
x = 0
a = [1,2,3]
y = 2
sum = 6 (even)
x + sum = 6 → even
y = 2 → even

👉 Alice ✅

⚡ FINAL CODE
long long sum = 0;
for (auto a : arr) sum += a;

if ((x + sum) % 2 == y % 2)
    cout << "Alice\n";
else
    cout << "Bob\n";
🧠 ONE-LINE MEMORY

👉 “Ignore everything → just match parity”
